<br>
What was that supposed to mean as she landed in North Karana. As she had fully expected, the little runters were there and immediately one ported off to, she assumed, the Moon, where she could report in. <br>
<br>
&quot;Now ye come easy lassy and there'll be no 'arm done to ye,&quot; another, bolder runter had the temerity to spout.  Stormygale laughed in her face, and quickly summoned her steed. Doom materialized and pawed the ground, tired it seemed of being pent up in the stables, and the sheer size of him intimidating all to back away. &quot;You should let it lie, little runter, before you get hurt,&quot; she responded,&quot; then wheeled Doom and sped away. She bent around and watched the pursuers falling far behind. <br>
<br>
The fun of riding almost made her pain seem immaterial. After zoning into South Karana, she let loose the reins and gave Doom his head. He reared once, pawing the air with white hooves, then sped away. In no time at all she was zoning again, and then again into another zone and then her destination, the zone of Rathe Mountains. <br>
<br>
She trotted past hill giants and cyclops now too frightened of her to come near. Believe it or not, there was an inn here and if you knew the innkeepers secret password, no harm would come to you. Abruzi had often honored it. No questions asked, and now she would ask for the same.  <br>
<br>
She dismounted and gave Doom a pat. Oh what a wonderful investment he'd been. Always at hand in need and completely loyal. &quot;Off you go then lad,&quot; she whispered into his ear. &quot;Have a bit of grass and a good roll and I'll be out in a bit. I have business inside.&quot; She gave his rump another pat and watched fondly as he squealed and ran and kicked up his heels in a fit of bucking, then got down to the business of good green grass.<br>
<br>
Stormygale grimaced yet again in pain, but standing tall, she entered the inn. She strode up to the rather sly looking fellow obviously in charge of this seedy place. His evil eyes lit on her like a man on pure gold. The greed showing through like little suns from his eyes. <br>
<br>
She threw $100 plat on the counter and said the word. The man's entire demeanor changed. &quot;Yes mum, anything you says mum,&quot; was all that came out of his mouth at her requests. She gathered up her goods and waved him a goodbye, but he didn't see it as he was too busy polishing more money than he'd seen in a long, long time. <br>
<br>
She whistled once outside and Doom immediately nickered and came forward. Most of his white hide, which once had been black, much as her own hair, was now stained green. Luckily they'd take care of him back at the stables. She simply was unable to groom him anymore. &quot;Did you have fun? she asked, and got another nicker in return. &quot;Well, off we go then,&quot; and she mounted up and memorized the port to Wakening Lands. In a trice she was gone.<br>
<br>
When they rematerialized there was Wuoshi to greet them. While she eyed Doom with great interest, she didn't give a hoot about Stormygale, and that was all that was required. She invised up and sped off through the woods, knowing well to keep away from the entrance to her Gods land. She did not want to be seen. Doom dodged through the wood like a trained acrobat, which he was and after stopping for one moment to trample a panther into the ground, she had reached her destination. <br>
<br>
She dismounted for the last time for a while she hoped, and almost collapsed. Doom stood stoically and braced her until she could get her feet under her. &quot;What a wonderful horse you are, Doom. I love you so much,&quot; Stormygale used his mane to wipe her face from tears of glee as much as pain. &quot;You go home now and they'll rub you down and feed you well. I hear there is a new mare in the stall next to yours now,&quot; and watched as Doom took on his stallion Stance. Head up, chest out, snorting and blowing in glee. &quot;You big fool. Good luck with her!&quot; and watched as he vanished. <br>
<br>
She entered Skyshrine and nodded to the two guards. They knew her from days past and let her enter unquestioned. They were not about to tell anyone she was here. They cared not at all about puny human concerns.<br>
<br>
Well, let them find her now, she thought as she selected a room not too far from the merchants. Yes, they had a brew which would work fine and she bought many a bottle. In fact, she was already drinking one as she made her bed and had started the third as she kicked off her boots. She'd been smart enough to buy edible supplies in Rathe Mountains, as the dragon's food was not to her liking. Too hard to digest. She tore into a piece of jerky and sipped her brew and slowly fell asleep yet again as the pain abated. Her last thought was a brief puzzle over the words of Athene. Can help. Can help what? Who? It didn't matter anyway....<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p><b>Stormygale El`Orian</b><img border=0 src="http://www.cpmission.com/graphics/icons/icon45.gif" /></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markvisual>Mark Visual</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Officer</span><br>  Posts: 1416<br> <font color=#7A8798>(7/18/03 11:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.battle.net/war3/images/undead/units/animations/lich.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Sitting here in the now empty seats of the Theatre of Mischief was usually a good quiet spot to be left alone when researching spells, and Vandergrave did not want to be disturbed while working out the arcane details of her newest desire, The Funeral Pyre of Kelador.<br>
<br>
She stopped for a moment in mid-scribe, sensing the usual morning break from her work.<br>
<br>
“Bah! Where be the Cazic-Thule Puppet!! Ridiculously funny!” shouted Fizzlethorpe Bristlebane as he appeared in front of her, right on schedule. “You know Fizzlethorpe, you ask that same question everytime you decide to manifest yourself. And, as of yet, none of your denizens has brought you that damn puppet. Nor do I think they ever will.”<br>
<br>
Bristlebane winked at Vandergrave and nudged her in the rib, “Bah! Where’s your sense of humor Necromancer! There be no harm in asking!” Vandergrave raised an eyebrow at Bristlebane, “I have no sense of humor, hobbit.” She said with a smirk. “Well, I best retire to me chambers then, hurry and finish that spell some day will you?…I’d like me home to myself at some point.” said Bristlebane, vanishing as quickly as he appeared, and with just as big of a grin. It was true, Vandergrave could be humorless and dry at times, but she almost sort of liked that giant Hobbit (as much as one could like the living, anyway), and she did owe him at least a conversation or two since he was kind enough to let her reside in his Plane from time to time.<br>
<br>
 Just then, Vandergrave felt a disturbance. Words of green mist appeared in her mind, just out of sight. Her guild was calling to her…..something she could not quite make out. Sto….a story? No…Storm…..Why would they warn her of a storm…Shadowha…Shadowhaven…That was on Luclin….No storms there….Stormygale. That was it. Stormygale was in trouble.<br>
<br>
Vandergrave quickly but away her quill and parchment, picking up her Scythe. “Suspend yourself Garn,” she said to the Child Of Bertoxxulos, “The one that brought you to me is in need, and we must travel.” The sickening visage floated behind Vandergrave, placing it’s rotting, skeletal hands on her shoulders before whispering into her ears, “As you wish, Oh Splendid One…” It’s breath smelled of an abandoned slaughterhouse, but she had long since become accoustmed to such unpleasantries. Garn then vanished, folding inwards into his own robes, leaving behind only a thin ribbon of grave mist.<br>
<br>
She quickly opened a Gate, stepping from the Theatre into the main hall of the castle, then through a secret doorway into the Courtyards. She ran south to the Planar Portal, suddenly shifting from the Planes into reality. The shift into the Cobalt Scar was always unpleasant, going from warm, dry air to cold, icy water. As she swam her way to the Druid Circle, making sure to activate her Circlet of Shadow so that the acursed Othmir would not hinder her. She wanted to cover her ears as she ran through the Othmir camp. That music…Innoruuk’s glare! That awful music!<br>
 <br>
Vandergrave began to form a response, the green script forming mystically in her mind. “I am on my way.” She willed to the ether. She only hoped is was not too late…<br>
